05265nam a22007935i 9781503609396DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202019cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2018047094  a97815036093967 a10.1515/97815036093962doi  a(DE-B1597)563955  a(OCoLC)1178768929  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aDS110.W47bD4 2019 4aDS110.W47 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a363.6909569421 aDe Cesari, Chiara, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHeritage and the Cultural Struggle for Palestine /cChiara De Cesari. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Studies in Middle Eastern and Islamic Societies and Cultures00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on Transliteration -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. The Stakes of Heritage and the Politics of Culture -- tChapter 1. A Political History of Palestinian Heritage -- tChapter 2. Government Through Heritage in Old Hebron -- tChapter 3. Heritage, NGOs, and State Making -- tChapter 4. Palestinian National Museums Post-Oslo -- tConclusion. Cultural Governmentality and Activist Statehood -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent decades, Palestinian heritage organizations have launched numerous urban regeneration and museum projects across the West Bank in response to the enduring Israeli occupation. These efforts to reclaim and assert Palestinian heritage differ significantly from the typical global cultural project: here it is people's cultural memory and living environment, rather than ancient history and archaeology, that take center stage. It is local civil society and NGOs, not state actors, who are "doing" heritage. In this context, Palestinian heritage has become not just a practice of resistance, but a resourceful mode of governing the Palestinian landscape. With this book, Chiara De Cesari examines these Palestinian heritage projects—notably the Hebron Rehabilitation Committee, Riwaq, and the Palestinian Museum—and the transnational actors, practices, and material sites they mobilize to create new institutions in the absence of a sovereign state. Through their rehabilitation of Palestinian heritage, these organizations have halted the expansion of Israeli settlements. They have also given Palestinians opportunities to rethink and transform state functions. Heritage and the Cultural Struggle for Palestine reveals how the West Bank is home to creative experimentation, insurgent agencies, and resourceful attempts to reverse colonial violence—and a model of how things could be.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCultural propertyzWest Bank. 0aHistoric sitesxConservation and restorationzWest Bank. 0aNational museumszWest Bank. 0aPalestinian ArabsxPolitics and governmenty1993- 0aPalestinian ArabsxPolitics and governmenty1993-. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAnthropology of Palestine.  aNGOs and cultural development.  aanticolonial resistance.  acultural policy.  acultural politics.  aheritage and memory.  amuseums.  astate and institution building.  aurban planning.  aurban regeneration.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package: